Reload your shell once (source ~/.zshrc) and you'll have these shortcuts available from any directory:

Command	What it does
jk-serve	Start / restart the Jekyll container
jk-rebuild	Rebuild image from scratch (use after Gemfile changes)
jk-stop	Stop the container
jk-logs	Tail live Jekyll output
jk-open	Open http://localhost:4000 in browser
jk-push "your message"	git pull --rebase → commit all → push
The same commands work as make targets when you're inside the project directory:


make serve
make rebuild
make push MSG="add new portfolio project"
Note: For regular content edits (markdown, HTML, YAML) you don't need to restart Docker at all — the container already runs with Jekyll's -w watch flag and will regenerate automatically within a few seconds of saving.

---


# Convert .bib files (drop them in files/bibtex/ first)
make bib

# Or from anywhere
jk-bib

# Or target a specific file
python3 scripts/bib_to_md.py files/bibtex/mypaper.bib
What it handles automatically:

BibTeX field	→ Jekyll field
doi	doiurl
eprint + archivePrefix: arXiv	arxivurl
url (arxiv.org)	arxivurl
url (other)	paperurl
author	IEEE-formatted citation with your name bolded
abstract	body content + truncated excerpt
Fields left as # TODO for you to fill manually:

paperurl — direct PDF/Drive link
codeurl — GitHub repo